Three endangered cheetah cubs were born in Iran
The world's fastest animal falls victim to brutal hunting, droughts and fatal road accidents across the Islamic Republic
As a result, the number dropped to less than 20 cheetahs.
Three Asian cheetah cubs have recently emerged from the Islamic Republic of Iran.
This is a rare birth, which only slightly improves the tragic condition of the endangered animal in the country following droughts, hunters and fatal traffic accidents.
This is the first birth of a captive cheetah in Iran.
It should be noted that the Islamic Republic is one of the last countries in the world where cheetahs still live in the wild.
The Iranian news agency IRNA reported that the veterinary team, which is responsible for the Thoran National Park in the northern Semnan Province, decided on an imperial birth in captivity.
It was also noted that fewer than 20 cheetahs have been recorded in seven different provinces in the country.
As a result of the threat to their extinction, the UN implemented a defense plan for them back in 2001.
Now, Iran hopes that the new cubs will be able to increase the cheetah population in the future.
In January, Iran's deputy environment minister Hassan Akbari said the country's cheetah population had dropped dramatically from 100 in 2010 to just 12.
"Their situation is extremely serious," Akbari said, noting that cheetahs have fallen victim to drought in their habitats, hunting and even traffic accidents.
The cheetah is considered the fastest animal in the world, capable of reaching a speed of 100 km/h.
Cheetahs can be found in various places across the globe, from India to Senegal in West Africa.
Spotify wants to upgrade your car: We tested the Car Thing
Quietly, Spotify began to try its luck even in the hardware world
After years of development, Car Thing was unveiled and launched as a small experiment in the US
We got our hands on the first device in Israel
The idea is to make your old cars smart.
The Car Thing is Spotify's first hardware product, and was built specifically to provide a solution for people with older vehicles.
A few weeks ago, I got an initial opportunity to try the new product, which is currently only available to individual experimenters in the US, here in Israel.
For me, the timing of the delivery was outstanding, as our home vehicle broke down and we had to drive for several days with an old system replacement vehicle.
After two weeks of playing around, I realized how the Car Thing could easily become an integral part of many people's system.
On the other hand, with a long waiting list and uncertainty about a global launch, I believe that many will prefer to use other solutions.
From Idea to Reality.
Somewhere in 2018, Spotify users began to get an interesting offer in their email box - the option to purchase a new device with voice control and fourth-generation connectivity, which would make any old car system smart.
The rumors slowly faded until a year later, when the Financial Times website revealed that the company plans to soon introduce a new product for a vehicle that simulates a smart radio with Bluetooth connectivity.
A few months later, those rumors were back in the headlines again after the music service was updated with the status of the vehicle - the same one we now know from the app - operated as soon as the smartphone detects a connection to the system in the car.
Two years have passed.
After numerous rumors and leaks, Spotify unveiled "Car Thing" in April, its smart system for vehicles.
Spotify has chosen to release the new device in a very limited way, with a long waiting list and many delays when it comes to deliveries.
So of course, right after the press conference, I went on the website and signed up.
Two months later, the long-awaited announcement came.
Reconnecting to the site will buy me the opportunity to purchase the device with a little surprise - it will not cost me anything.
After another month of waiting, the courier finally knocked on my door, accompanied by a small box with the Spotify logo on it.
The car thing.
First and foremost, Spotify's device impressed me greatly with the quality of its construction.
And a little smaller than my iPhone 11 and features a large, bright, sharp touch screen in front of it than I expected.
You'll also find a circular button and dial next to the screen that you can rotate to navigate between the interface screens.
And despite the huge dial, which you can see in the pictures, the Car Thing manages to keep a relatively thin profile and not stand out too much from the dashboard.
Personally, I would prefer that the company allow me to change the dial activity so that I can control the volume of the smartphone, since I can also navigate through the touch screen.
Perhaps this will be possible in a future revision.
The device comes in a small and minimalist cardboard box, which includes a USB Type C cable and various adapters for its installation.
Many of you may remember how in the past we used to disconnect the radios and hide them in a drawer after getting out of the car.
The Car Thing certainly brings that feeling back with its construction form.
All the adapters connected to the body of the device using a magnet that was very strong, which prevented it from falling even when traveling on dirt roads.
In addition, all along the top you can find small buttons, which can be easily configured to play different playlists or podcasts.
By pressing one of the buttons while listening, or by asking the voice assistant, I set up some of the playlists I listen to frequently and the radio show I listen to every morning on the road.
In doing so, the feature made me feel that the Car Thing is more like a car radio than an extension of my smartphone.
An old car for a smart car
After a fairly simple physical installation, I plugged in the Car Thing.
I was pleasantly surprised by the process.
The instructions were clear, the connection to the Spotify app took less than 5 minutes, and a few moments later I reached the home screen.
In fact, the device connects to the smartphone through Bluetooth and controls the app like a remote control, and therefore can copy all the information about our account from it.
That means you'll still have to connect your smartphone to your car, whether through Bluetooth or an AUX cable to hear the music.
The home screen is familiar to all users of the app, since like the application on a smartphone, it emphasizes album photos and playlists.
Also, on the home screen, like the one in the app, you can find music recommendations according to your taste, the search screen, and your personal library.
As mentioned, you can navigate between the different screens using the touch screen or using the hand dial.
Moreover, at any given moment, you can call the device's voice assistant by saying "Hey Spotify."
With it, you can play songs, playlists, albums and even search for podcasts.
From my experience, she recognized my voice quite easily even when the music was playing in the background and the air conditioner blew directly on the device.
This is probably due to the four microphones installed at the top.
It is important to note that at the moment the voice assistant does not support Hebrew, and as of the time of publication of the article, there is no information on when such an update will arrive.
Is it worth waiting for him?
My experience using the device was great, which is a positive surprise to me considering that it is still in the initial release stage.
Even with intensive use on long trips, the device continued to work smoothly without disconnecting from my smartphone.
Nevertheless, from time to time there is a small stutter in the interface, but I believe Spotify will handle such bugs with future version updates.
It is evident that the Swedish company has worked on it a lot in recent years, and among the various versions leaked on the Internet during this period, the design of the final product is probably my favorite.
Still, when I first saw the Car Thing, I wondered who exactly the company was trying to designate it to.
After all, his activity comes down to controlling the smartphone app, and not much else.
What's different from buying a car stand for a few shekels and connecting it so that the smartphone will be closer to us when driving?
This question is reinforced when considering that iPhone and Android devices are much more powerful than Spotify's, and in most cases will buy the user much more functionality.
Nevertheless, as I used Car Thing more and more, I realized how it could improve the driving experience.
Being able to see Waze on my smartphone screen and control music on a completely different screen is one I've come to appreciate over the past two weeks.
One question remains - will Spotify even launch the device to the general public?
And if so, will it also be launched here in our small country?
The Swedish company isn't saying much right now.
It hasn't even shared how many test-takers it's currently running worldwide, and how much it plans to add in the limited launch in the United States.
The only thing we know for sure is that the price is expected to be $79 (about NIS 255).
In the meantime, the Car Thing provides an initial glimpse of a concept Spotify has been trying to crack for years.
Spotify Israel said that there is currently no information on a plan to launch the device in Israel.
