Job market: fewer job applicants, more wages
The Al-Jobs Report for 2021: Top Demand - Jobs Without Experience
Jobs offered increased by 50%.
"You're looking for a job, but you're not hitting the market."
In the year that just ended, there was a 15% decrease in the number of resumes sent, and on each position only 23 candidates ran, compared to 41 candidates in the previous year, according to a report by the Aljubes website for the year 2021, about the COVID-19 crisis and its effects on the labor market in Israel.
According to the report, job seekers were primarily interested in jobs such as administration and sales, for which 1,738,485 resumes were sent.
However, the inexperienced jobs led the way in demand with more than 38,000 searches - apparently following the return of young people with no professional experience to search for immediate work, at the end of the IAF's payments.
The number of searches for sales and administration was 35,000 and 32,000 (respectively), the drivers and couriers had 11,000 searches, and the retention had slightly less than 9,000 searches.
On the other hand, despite the COVID-19 crisis, wages in 2021 increased by 2% compared to 2020, and the average wage in Israel was NIS 11,675 gross.
The monthly salary in the field of software was NIS 17,915 on average, and in information systems analysis it was NIS 17,140.
However, between the center and the periphery there was a wage gap of more than 2,000 shekels: in the center of the country it was 12,500 shekels on average, compared to 10,795 shekels in the north and 10,135 shekels in the south.
From a gender perspective, the average wage gap between women and men, which can also be explained by the type of work and the amount of hours, was maintained at 36%.
Men earned 13,295 shekels, while women earned 9,740 shekels.
Trying to get back in line.
On the business side, there was across-the-board growth in almost all sectors of the economy, and businesses craved working hands.
Thus, the supply of jobs increased by 50% and recorded a record of more than 40,000 jobs at Al-Jobs.
A survey conducted by the site among employers found that 50% were optimistic about their economic status in 2022, 30% of them indicated their intention to increase total recruitment but 72% understand that they will have a hard time doing so this year.
The largest supply was for inexperienced jobs - and there were more than 58,000 at the site.
They were followed by customer service and administrative positions with about 44,000 jobs in each field, sales and software with 41,000 jobs each, teaching and education with 24,000 jobs available, and warehouses still in demand with 19,000 vacancies.
Einav Boimfeld, Director of Research and Content at Al-Jobs: "Job seekers are trying to get back on track but are not storming the market, mainly due to the lack of attractive jobs in their eyes.
Also, the long disconnect from the workforce makes it difficult for them to return, and some have found creative ways to make a living. "
Israel's unemployment rate rises to 6.3%
According to the Bureau's survey, 270,000 Israelis remained unemployed in December 2021.
In November, 262,000 people were unemployed.
The unemployment rate in the first half of December 2021 was 6.3 percent, about 270,000 Israelis, compared with 6.1 percent in the second half of November 2021 (about 262,000).
This is according to data from the Labor Force Survey for the first half of December 2021 of the Central Bureau of Statistics.
Unemployment stood at 4.5% in the first half of December 2021 compared to 4.3% in the second half of November 2021.
