State Comptroller's Report: The Actual Budget for Most Years of the Drug Basket Committee's Activity is Less Than the Recommended Budget
According to the report of Matanyahu Engelman, during the more than 20 years of activity of the basket, the Ministry of Health did not supervise the activities of the committee.
The report also states that the minutes of the meetings are being published significantly late, if at all.
In addition, the Comptroller recommends increasing the transparency of the subcommittee's activities and updating the basket work procedures.
Another flaw found relates to the fact that since the committee began its activities, the Ministry of Health has not asked the health funds for reports on the extent of the use and utilization of the drugs in the basket - which would have made it possible to analyze and control the budget given to them.
The Pharmaceutical Basket Committee is one of the most influential public committees on our daily lives and health.
Every year, the committee decides on new drugs that will be given to the public free of charge through the health funds - but a new report by the State Comptroller published on Tuesday warns that it has been operating for more than 20 years without any control reports on its activity and without the Ministry of Health and the Health Council monitoring and examining its activity.
Israel Hayom correspondent Ran Reznik adds that the State Comptroller's investigation was conducted following the ongoing exposures in Israel Hayom about the drug basket failures.
According to the report by Matanyahu Engelman, he recommends "making repairs and improvements in the basket expansion process, which will lead to a better quality utilization of the health basket budget to which the public is entitled."
Throughout the years of the addition mechanism to the basket of medicines, in the years 1998-2021, NIS 8 billion were added to the state budget, with the addition moving annually in amounts ranging from NIS 0 to NIS 500 million.
In 2019, 2020 and 2021, applications were submitted to add about 800 new drugs and technologies to the healthcare basket, at a total annual cost of more than NIS 2 billion.
In practice, the budget allocated for expanding the basket was smaller than the scope of the requests.
In most years of the committee's activity (90% of the time), the budgetary increase was less than 1.5% of the health basket, a rate recommended by various committees as the desired increase rate.
The comptroller notes that it is necessary to examine and regulate the amount of the annual supplement in order to enable certainty and long-term planning.
Engelman also noted that "the transparency model in basket work is lacking."
Thus, for example, the Hassel Committee's work procedure states that the minutes of the meetings, which are closed to the public, will be published within 60 days, but in practice the minutes are published with a delay of 160-109 days, when sometimes the minutes of the final meetings are not published at all.
"The delay in the publication of the protocols harms the transparency of the decisions; as a result, the ability of the submitters of the proposals - hospital organizations and pharmaceutical companies - to submit repeated requests as soon as possible and as relevant, after they learned lessons from the rejection of their proposals, analyzed the reasons for their failure in the previous round, improved and revised their proposals and reassessed the feasibility of accepting them in the next round," the Comptroller noted in the report.
"The Ministry of Health must publish the protocols in accordance with the schedules set forth in the procedure."
Out of thousands of submissions, only one financial comment was submitted.
Another criticism of Engelman relates to the preliminary process of evaluating the technologies submitted to the basket of medicines.
The comptroller found that about half (46%) of the technologies submitted did not pass this stage, but the Ministry of Health does not publish the reasons for the rejection.
Another impairment relates to the activities of the Drug Basket subcommittee, which is closed to the media and the public, and in which patient numbers and costs of drugs are discussed.
The Comptroller recommends that a public representative be appointed or that the possibility of publicizing the discussions to the public be examined without confidential commercial details.
According to the procedure by which the Health Services Basket Committee operates, "an economic assessment must be submitted" for a request to add a drug to the basket.
But in practice, over the years only one of thousands of submissions has been submitted - and the committee makes its decisions without an economic assessment.
For example, the Hassel Committee's hearings for 2021-2019 submitted requests to add anti-obesity drugs to the basket.
The report found that the requests did not include economic estimates, including an estimate of the amount that could have been saved due to reducing the damage of obesity-related diseases or due to the ability to avoid gastric surgery.
It also emerges that the decisions of the Pharmaceutical Basket Committee are not in line with the goals and strategy of the Ministry of Health.
Thus, for example, in 2019, the Ministry of Health defined preventive medicine and preparations for the treatment of tumors in chronic diseases as goals, but in the framework of the decisions regarding the expansion of the basket, no emphasis was placed on the need to achieve these goals.
The Comptroller also warns that since 2011, services that are not under the responsibility of the HMOs have also been included in the basket of medicines, including rehabilitation and mobility devices and various vaccines, which are given by the Ministry of Health (the "Third Supplement").
This is when the legal framework for this step is regulated only retroactively.
In the past six years, NIS 74 million of the supplement to the medical basket has been used for these services.
Engelman recommends that the Ministry of Health update the basket work procedures and also determine whether a separate financial supplement is needed for these services.
About a third of the new drugs that enter the basket are defined as "drugs with no additional cost," whose use does not cost the health funds an additional amount because they replace existing treatment.
The Comptroller proposes to examine the possibility that these drugs will be discussed in a different and abbreviated track, so that the basket of drugs can be updated several times a year and not only once a year.
There is no control over the use of expensive drugs.
The criticism also indicates that since the ETF began its work 20 years ago, the Ministry of Health has not asked HMOs to report and has not supervised the scope of the use and utilization of the drugs in the basket, information that could have enabled the Ministry to analyze and audit the budget given to the health plans.
Over the years, only two reports relating to the years 2006-2009 were published, and these too were published with considerable delay (the last one was published this year and dealt with the utilization of the budget in 2007-2009).
"The delay in conducting examinations may lead to difficulty in collecting and analyzing the data, to the irrelevance of the conclusions arising from the examination after such a long period, to improper pricing of the subcommittee and to decisions based on inconclusive findings," the report said.
In addition, the Ministry also does not review and supervise the use of particularly expensive drugs and has not learned any lessons.
These are 10 drugs that constituted 62% of the addition to the basket (NIS 1.7 billion in the years 2021-2016).
The comptroller wrote: "It is recommended that the Ministry of Health conduct individual controls on these drugs and technologies and analyze the extent of their use in comparison with the estimates.
Controls and analysis will make it possible to draw systemic conclusions about the work process of the basket committee and the subcommittee, and about how to prepare and improve estimates when pricing drugs and technologies. "
