About the late Prof. Marvin Shapira
The meeting that opened my eyes - and changed my life
Had I not met the late Prof. Marvin Shapira, who was the director of the infectious diseases unit at Hadassah Hospital, I probably would have remained a specialist in internal medicine.
He is the one who made me love the field of infectious diseases and influenced me to engage in it.
I met him in the halls of Hadassah, back in the 1980s.
For a moment I didn't think I would leave the inner room, because I loved the treatment of the patient himself; but Prof. Shapira showed me that the field of infectious diseases is also expressed in neurology, also in the inner room, and in virtually every area.
Thank you for bringing me into this field.
All along, I liked his investigative approach, one that gets to the root of the problem.
Discussions with him were analytical and logical.
He was a doctor with every fiber of his soul, who loved the sick and taught me not to take things for granted and to look into everything.
He was a real, honest man, devoid of ego, qualities I loved very much about him.
Initially, when I was asked to choose a doctor who was my role model and influenced me the most, I intended to choose my father, Dr. Yosef Rakover z "l, a Holocaust survivor who served as a doctor in a partisan unit.
He was an amazing doctor, who inspired me to go into medicine - but he also reminds me of Marvin Shapiro.
Both, for example, coined proverbs that doctors use to this day - for example, "Tissot Is de Ishio," that is, taking a tissue biopsy from the infected organ makes it possible to know which drugs should be given; or "Won Yoo Hughes It, Yoo Luz It," which is meant to explain that overuse of antibiotics leads to bacteria becoming resistant to it.
Prof. Shapira was married to a physiotherapist who worked at Hadassah and had two daughters.
He died a year ago, and when I visited his family at seven I cried.
He was something - a witty and clever epidemiologist, who volunteered for everything.
He never complained, not even during his illness.
He was one of the first doctors on the team to treat epidemics, and is sorely missed during this period.
Had he been with us today, I'm sure I would have consulted with him, and I'm sure he would have been one of the leaders of the pandemic treatment team.
