Medical malpractice during the different stages of birth
In order to win compensation, the plaintiffs must prove, in addition to the negligence, that the damage was caused by that negligence.
Childbirth is one of the most joyous and exciting events in the life of a family.
However, unfortunately, sometimes births end in severe damage caused to the mother or the newborn as a result of the negligence of the medical staff.
In cases where the birth ended in physical injury, to a newborn or mother, there is room to examine the sequence of events that led to the injury and even consider seeking legal advice.
A lawyer specializing in the field of medical negligence will examine whether there were defects in the conduct of the medical team during the various stages of birth that caused the damage and, as far as he sees fit, will consult a medical expert in the relevant field.
It should be emphasized that not every mistake in treatment on the part of the medical staff amounts to negligence (in the legal sense of this term) and that various complications during childbirth do not necessarily indicate that management was negligent.
When is it about negligence?
When the doctor's error was due to a lack of skill or deviation from the reasonable level of caution, and the lack of skill and deviation from the usual level of caution caused harm to the patient that would not have been caused had the doctor not done so.
In this article, we will examine the various stages of childbirth, explain what complications may occur at each stage and when they rise to medical malpractice.
The Axes Stage
The contraction stage lasts an average of 8 to 14 hours.
At this stage, the cervix is gradually opened (in order to allow the fetal passage at birth) and at the end of the process should reach a diameter of about ten centimeters.
Most cases of medical negligence at the contraction stage deal with the failure to identify fetal distress prior to birth, which caused damage to the newborn, which is sometimes even expressed in cerebral palsy.
Cerebral Palsy (CP):
Cerebral palsy may be caused by non-identification or delay in the identification of perinatal asphyxia, which results in a failure in the supply of oxygen to the fetal brain tissue.
As a rule, monitoring the mother's condition and correct decryption of the fetal heart monitor should lead to early identification of fetal distress development, allowing the medical team to act quickly and rescue the newborn before it is irreversibly damaged.
In cases where the medical team ignores signs indicating that the fetus is suffering from a lack of oxygen or that the team is not interpreting the data correctly and in particular the fetal monitor or responds late to the distress expressed in the monitor - this may constitute negligence.
Cerebral palsy may also be caused by the prolapse of the umbilical cord as well as a rupture in the uterus that was not detected in a timely manner.
Even in these difficult events, it is worth finding out whether the medical team acted properly.
For example, Adv. Anna Rafe Liganza, of Caspi Srour & Co., a firm specializing in representing victims of medical malpractice, says that her firm handled a claim of a child who was injured during his birth after the midwife ruptured the amniotic sac when the head of the fetus was too high, thereby causing the umbilical cord to prolapse (when the umbilical cord precedes the head of the fetus) and damage to the supply of oxygen to the fetal brain (as a result of pressure from the head of the fetus on the umbilical cord) and to be born with a severe neurological injury.
In another case, the lawyer said that her office filed a claim due to serious medical negligence of the maternity department staff at a large hospital, which during the birth did not identify at the time any clear signs that required a real suspicion that the woman suffered a rupture of the uterus in the surgical scar area of her previous pregnancy.
The embryo that was ejected through the rupture in its mother's womb into the abdominal cavity suffered severe fetal distress until it was rescued at a later stage, when it was on the verge of death.
Due to the severe fetal suffering during his birth, the child suffered a complex neurological disability.
It should be emphasized that in order to be awarded compensation, the plaintiffs must prove, in addition to negligence, that there is a causal connection between the negligence of the medical staff that led to the failure to identify the child and the damage caused to the newborn, that is, that the damage was caused as a result of the aforesaid negligence and not from any other reason or factor.
An examination of the causal relationship will be carried out by examining medical indices that according to the medical literature only exist when there is a causal connection between the brain injury and the brain injury.
Among other things, the measurements of the level of acidity in the embryo's blood, its Apgar scores, the existence of neurological and systemic damage, and more are examined.
Passing the Pass.
The active birth stage.
The active stage of labor begins when the cervical opening reaches a diameter of 10 centimeters and ends with the birth of the baby.
Unfortunately, most medical complications occur during this critical stage.
Delay in childbirth and avoidance of cesarean section
In some cases, dysfunctional birth develops, i.e., a lack of progression of the active birth process.
In such situations, it is customary to perform a cesarean section, in order to prevent various damage that may be caused to the fetus due to the delay in birth.
"There are cases in which failure to perform a caesarean section in a timely manner may cause irreparable damage to the fetus," explained attorney Rafe-Liganza.
"For example, we conducted a medical malpractice claim for a newborn death caused by a significant delay in performing a cesarean section.
In contrast to any known medical practice, the medical staff did not succeed in identifying the fetal distress and performing a cesarean section despite the particularly slow progression of the birth.
The delay in performing the surgery caused extensive systemic damage to the birth, which eventually led to her death shortly after birth. "
Vacuum birth negligence
In situations where the mother or the fetus is in significant danger that requires an especially rapid termination of the birth, a vacuum birth is sometimes performed (an empty studio).
In this process, a "dome" vacuum is attached to the head of the fetus and the fetus is pulled out by force.
Naturally, this action is fraught with dangers and can cause damage to both the fetus and the mother, and therefore requires great caution, precision and skill.
In these cases, medical malpractice may be expressed in the fact that the doctor does not adhere to the binding guidelines and performs the action despite the existence of a contraindication, such as when the head of the fetus is too high in the pelvis, or performs it for a longer time than permitted, or when despite the failure of a large number of attempts, the doctor continues and repeats the action more than the permitted number of attempts.
In such cases, if the negligent vacuum operation caused the newborn damage - among other things, it may cause cranial damage and bleeding that may cause brain damage - there is room for filing a tort claim.
It's called ERB.
Erb's paralysis is a congenital nerve injury in the brachial plexus (a nerve junction that connects the spine to the upper part of the shoulder) and when it occurs during childbirth, it is worth checking whether the damage occurred as a result of the negligence of the obstetric team.
The injury is manifested by weakness of the muscles of the hand and can reach the full paralysis of the entire arm.
This paralysis is often caused by a difficulty in removing the newborn due to the occurrence of a "shoulder disorder" - a midwifery emergency that occurs when the fetus' shoulders are trapped in the birth canal after its head has come out.
When should you suspect that paralysis is caused by medical negligence?
In cases where the fetus's weight assessment indicated that it was a macrosomic embryo, meaning that it is expected to be born weighing more than 4.5 kg and in accordance with the instructions, it is better to deliver the mother by Caesarean section.
When the newborn's weight is over 4 kg, a cesarean section should be considered in light of the risk factors, including gestational diabetes and the prolongation of the second stage of labor.
In the event that the medical team ignores an abnormal weight assessment of the fetus or other risk factors and chooses to continue with vaginal birth and the risk of shoulder disorder and ERB paralysis is realized, there is a reasonable possibility that this is medical malpractice.
Indeed, in CA 2694/90, the Supreme Court ruled that "the risk that shoulder stenosis will occur during childbirth can be predicted in advance to some degree of accuracy, and the way to prevent shoulder stenosis, where there is a concern for its occurrence, is to perform a cesarean section."
The placental exit phase
The separation of the placenta from the uterus and its exit occurs due to the contraction of the uterus after the neonate exits and is accompanied by bleeding.
In most cases, the process lasts up to half an hour from the time the baby leaves and usually occurs spontaneously, without the involvement of the medical staff.
After the placenta is removed, the medical team will check whether the placenta is intact or if there are parts of the placenta left in the uterus.
Within this stage, complications may occur that may cause serious harm to the mother.
One of the known complications as a result of the residual placental in the uterus is called "Asherman syndrome," the scarring of the uterine wall results in inflammation caused by the residual placental in the uterus, a phenomenon that damages the uterine lining in a way that does not allow implantation of pregnancy.
Therefore, in cases where the medical team did not identify placental residues or did not take all measures to prevent damage to the endometrium despite the suspicion of placental residues in the uterus, it may be medical negligence and the case deserves a thorough examination by an experienced lawyer in the field.
Death of mother.
Death during childbirth is very rare.
In these cases, the event that was supposed to bring happiness and joy to the whole family becomes, unfortunately, the most tragic event for her.
In some cases, the medical team does not detect bleeding in the mother on time or respond late to such bleeding.
"For example," Rife-Liganza told us, "our firm filed a lawsuit regarding the death of a mother, when in that case the medical team ignored and did not respond to the mother's alarming vital signs, for many hours, and was late in diagnosing massive and uncontrolled bleeding that occurred as a known complication of the background disease from which she suffered."
"In another case," said attorney Rafe-Liganza, "our firm represented the relatives of a mother who died after giving birth to twins due to bleeding that originated in the C-section that was not properly sewn.
In that case, the mother complained of severe pain and weakness after the operation, but the medical team did not properly treat her complaints and her clinical condition, reacted late only after her body systems began to fail, which led to her death. "
Loss of uterus
In severe cases, medical malpractice at birth can lead to a hysterectomy, says attorney Rafe Lingza: "Our firm has managed a lawsuit against a hospital that is based on a hysterectomy due to medical malpractice after birth.
In that case, the mother, a 31-year-old woman, lost her uterus due to a lack of proper treatment for massive bleeding that was observed by the medical team after the birth, and yet no action was taken to prevent the damage. "
What are the compensations awarded in claims for medical negligence at birth?
Newborn compensation for injury due to medical negligence at birth includes many components of damage, with the most significant amounts given for pain and suffering, nursing and wage care, salary and pension losses for the injured person and even for his parents and other components of damage.
The compensation awarded to an injured minor for salary and pension losses is calculated in most cases based on the average wage in the economy.
In addition, the compensation also includes medical expenses, the cost of medical and rehabilitative accessories, the cost of accommodation for the baby's needs, mobility and more.
"The amount of compensation is determined in each case and according to its circumstances," recounts attorney Rafe-Liganza, and she adds that "today most claims on the grounds of medical negligence end in a compromise that weighs the chance and risk that each side has in conducting the procedure," but the lawyer added that "there are cases in which the procedure ends only in a judgment, in which case if the claim is not rejected, the plaintiffs will receive full compensation for all their damages, and for example, in a lawsuit that our firm conducted, the District Court ruled that a minor who suffered cerebral palsy due to a delay in identifying fetal distress will receive compensation in excess of ten million shekels."
Summarize
Medical malpractice at birth is undoubtedly the nightmare of every family.
In these cases, a proper legal examination of the sequence of events that caused the tragic outcome, by a lawyer skilled in managing claims on the grounds of medical negligence, can help you win the compensation you deserve.
