Police official: "We need government policy and goals"
The Israeli police have launched an operation to eradicate the phenomenon of illegal aliens, but the road is still long.
There is not a single entity in the State of Israel that incorporates this entire issue. "
"If we want to deal with the phenomenon of illegal aliens, government policy is required, and from it we must derive goals, missions and responsibilities.
Today, there is no single entity in the State of Israel that integrates this entire issue, "a senior police official told Israel Hayom.
Until a month and a half ago, prior to the escalation in the security situation, the phenomenon was expressed in some 20,000 to 30,000 illegal aliens who enter the fence every day through breaches.
In addition, between 100,000 and 110,000 Palestinians with work permits enter Israel every day through 34 supervised crossings.
It should be noted that Palestinians have been employed in Israel since the end of the Six-Day War, and the number of permits in each sector is limited by the quota set by the political echelon in accordance with the security, economic and political situation in the State of Israel.
The permits are issued by the IDF through the Coordination and Liaison Administration.
In light of this, the ISA is not necessarily a Palestinian whose entry is prohibited as a result of criminal involvement or connection to terrorist attacks, but rather in many cases Palestinians whose entry is prohibited because they do not meet the permissible permit quota.
It should be emphasized that those who carried out the attacks in Ariel, Dizengoff and Elad were considered illegal aliens, but were not supervised, because they had not previously committed any criminal offense that required security officials to monitor their movements.
"Therefore, there is no significance to their entry through the breaches in the fence," a senior security source said, "Anyone who wants to carry out a terrorist attack can enter the country through the supervised crossings, and there have been such cases in the past.
Thousands of arrests
Following the attack in Elad and in light of numerous warnings of attacks, the police launched a large-scale operation to locate illegal aliens.
By the end of the week, 16,000 illegals had been arrested.
Of these, about 600 were interrogated and criminal cases were opened, and about 200 were imprisoned.
According to the policy of the police prosecution, proceedings against illegal aliens are carried out only against habitual criminals or people who repeat the act over and over again (recidivism).
Illegal detainees detained for the first time are interrogated, documented and returned to the territories.
Sometimes this is repeated a second time, but only the third time he is arrested, imprisoned and indicted for unlawful stay.
According to the law, if an illegal alien is caught within a range of 50 to 100 meters on either side of the separation fence, his treatment is carried out by the military prosecution.
According to data obtained by Israel Hayom, in 2021 the police treated 40,010 illegal aliens, transporters and accomplices.
7,405 illegal aliens were arrested and 19,533 criminal cases were opened.
The number of employers, transporters and melons treated by the police in 2021 was 6,537.
469 were arrested, and 5,640 criminal cases were opened.
"The foundations of the Shin Bet phenomenon do not depend on the police, the IDF, Israeli society or Palestinian society.
They depend on other factors, "says a senior law enforcement official.
"In order to deal with the phenomenon, their motivation to work in Israel must be sterilized, and on the Israeli side they must be charged a price that will prevent them from crossing the fence.
Sources involved in the matter claim that the failure to charge the price stems, among other things, from a lack of places of detention and from the fact that the arrests are carried out only when there are incidental offenses or that the detainee is a recidivist.
Legal sources claim that the decision to charge a price from the IPS only began with his third arrest, partly because the courts cannot cope with the number of arrests carried out every day.
Anyone who examines the punishment will find that it is not deterring. "
There is great complexity
A police official said, "He's a complicated man."
He can be a father of a family who came to Israel to work to earn a few shekels and come back.
This is the basic platform, and on it are dressed many types of illegals who enter the country to commit criminal offenses or terrorist attacks. "
It can be an adult or a minor.
In the past, 16-year-old illegal aliens have been caught by the police, and even 8- and 10-year-old children are sent by their parents to intersections to earn a few shekels a day from drivers.
"It also makes it complicated, because in such cases we have to bring the parents and charge them with negligence," says a senior police officer.
Most Palestinians are employed in Israel.
The most unusual are electrical work or advanced construction work.
In the past, there were also local authorities that employed illegals in garbage disposal, mainly in the north.
Out of 34 passes, there are about 18 major ones.
There are crossings of vehicles and goods, there are crossings through which only people pass, and there are crossings that are both.
All the crossings are supervised by the IDF and the Crossings Authority.
The illegal immigrants are usually transported into the country by private drivers, as this is easy money.
"There are those who do this for a living and there are gangs whose main occupation is transporting illegals," says a senior police official, "Most of them are Israeli Arabs, who speak the same language and correspond with them.
It can cost up to $300 per person.
Registered companies do not deal with this, because if the company is caught, it will be closed. "
The police emphasize that under certain conditions, transporting illegals can be considered a crime.
"A taxi driver who works with licenses and insurance, who picks up Palestinians at regular points and at regular times, including an order, does not break the law," says a senior police official, "Anyone who knows he is driving an illegal alien, usually collects them in the dead of night at hiding spots, including downloading at hidden spots.
Most of these guys drive a half-assed car because they know we'll confiscate their car, so they prefer to drive an old car. "
