Study Says Zoom Meetings Harm Creativity
Some 2,100 engineers and academics around the world were asked to develop solutions to the problem - some in video sessions, some in face-to-face meetings.
The Result: Virtual Meeting Harms Creativity and Thinking Out of the Box
Columbia University research leader: "Visual focus on the screen impairs the idea-creation process"
Forte comfort: There is no harm to labor productivity or critical thinking.
A major scientific study recently published in the scientific journal Nature examined the impact of meetings through video programs on the creativity of their participants, compared to face-to-face meetings.
Unfortunately, creativity was found to be impaired in virtual meetings through screens.
The research question - led by Melanie Brooks, an assistant professor at Columbia University - was whether remote computer-aided meetings preserve the creativity that exists in office brainstorming sessions, or whether the level of creativity and free-thinking decreases as a result of remoteness.
The study itself began in 2016 but received a big boost in the two COVID-19 years, during which many employees switched to working from home.
"People in a personal meeting move around the room, use objects, and use them for creative thinking," Brooks says.
"In a computer meeting, however, the concentration on maintaining eye contact with others comes at the expense of creative activity in the brain.
The visual focus on the screen reduces cognition.
People are more focused on video when interacting, which impairs the broad and expansive idea-creation process. "
Space is shrinking.
To test the results of the experiment and ascertain whether they would be repeated, they were tested twice - once at Columbia University and again in real life - on engineers who knew each other from an early acquaintance.
At the university, the researcher divided a group of 602 faculty and students into two parts - one asked the subjects to meet in person and develop solutions to the problem, and the other asked them to do so through a computer.
At the same time, 1,490 engineers from five countries in Europe, the Middle East and South Asia were asked to share similarly and solve a problem presented to them in a new way.
In both cases, there was a decrease in creativity and out-of-the-box thinking among those who met virtually on video.
Jay Olson, a postdoctoral fellow at McGill University in Canada and a researcher on ways to measure creativity, was not involved in the study but was not surprised by the results.
In his opinion, as part of a thinking activity, people often look at their surroundings to help them create ideas, while in a video session, thinking converges on the screen and does not expand in a way that allows creativity.
"When the people in that room look around them and see the space, where there are objects and situations that can awaken new associations in them.
In contrast, the research shows that computer-based relationships change our attention so that we are more focused on the inside and the screen, and this way reduces innovation and the creation of ideas through looking at the environment and thinking out. "
No harm to critical thinking.
However, before managers run the employees back to the offices, the researchers note that "working through a computer did not harm productivity itself nor people's critical thinking about innovative proposals when they had to choose the best idea from a set of ideas.
In other words, the harm is focused solely on creativity and not on other forms of computer work. "
Professor Ellen Langer, a professor of psychology at Harvard University, also qualifies the findings.
"There's a difference between mere creativity, like new uses for Frisbee, and work solutions.
It's also possible that when employees are more relaxed after dating, or when they work from home, creativity will improve. "
Prof. Langer and Dr. Olson have also proposed a future study in which such meetings would be stopped for thinking situations and roaming the room to see how this activity would affect the final outcome.
Dr. Olson also suggested that, following the study, only brainstorming sessions would lead to employees returning to work, and as a general rule, he suggested not to be alarmed by a single study, but to carry out another study in the field.
"I wouldn't want employees to be forcibly returned and unhappy," he said.
