By 2050, the world will lose 80% of the water available for agriculture.
A new global study predicts a significant decline in the next 25 years
The Solution: Proper Management of Water Reservoirs
A disturbing new study published recently in the journal Earth's Future predicts that by 2050 the amount of water available for agriculture will decrease by about 80% if the rate of water consumption and the growth of the world's population remain in their current usage trends.
In the study, which included scientists from all the world's scientific agencies, the scientists summarized the total amount of rainwater, rivers and freshwater sources in the world and compared it to the need of humanity for agriculture.
The study's bleak conclusions show that currently the rate of water consumption has been doubling again and again in the last 10 years, while global warming is causing a decrease in rainfall in agricultural areas around the world.
According to the research data, 84% of the land designated for agriculture in the world will experience a severe shortage of rainwater.
One of the main conclusions of the study calls on farmers around the world to adapt agriculture to climate change and the seasons of the year, and to switch to cultivation methods that will make it easier for water to penetrate the soil in order to prevent the process of evaporation of water that will lead to widespread waste of rainwater.
The researchers also recommend that farmers working near saltwater sources use rainwater collection technologies to prevent it from flowing into the sea.
