We checked: What do the side effects say after the COVID-19 vaccine?
Many people who get vaccinated feel weak, feverish and tired after receiving the injection, while others feel nothing.
Could this indicate a stronger immune system of those who do experience these phenomena, or is it a baseless rumor?
As more and more people become vaccinated, the lack of information about the side effects continues to confuse and create rumors, most of which are untrue.
Is the immune system of those who developed side effects stronger than those whose bodies reacted less harshly to the vaccine, which might prove that their system is unable to fight off a foreign body entering the body?
"There are several levels of responses to the vaccine," says Dr. David Dvir, head of primary medicine at Meuhedet and a member of the advisory committee of the LCCM (Epidemic Treatment Team), reassuringly: "Headaches, fatigue, pain on the spot, these are the immediate responses of the immune system.
This is how the body reacts when a foreign body enters the system. "
Is there a correlation between the levels of antibodies that develop to the side effects?
"There is no correlation between feelings and the development of antibodies against the virus.
About 60-50% feel the side effects, but about 90% develop protection against the virus.
People who have developed strong responses have not been found to be more protected. "
"In the medical literature, there is no correlation between immediate response and the level of vaccination.
In some trials where people were also given placebo vaccines, about a quarter of them developed headaches.
It is also a mental component - how the person perceives the vaccine, if he expects there to be side effects.
Many of the phenomena that happen could also happen normally, but because the public has been vaccinated it attributes the reaction to the vaccine itself, and this is a bias that you see with regard to vaccines in general - attribution of phenomena that happen close to the vaccine and are attributed to it. "
According to Dr. Dvir, the reasons for the reported common symptoms, such as weakness and headaches, are not yet known.
Regarding myocarditis, opinions are divided.
"There are all kinds of theories on the subject, but it should be noted that the virus itself causes higher rates of myocarditis than the vaccine.
One theory is that it's a strong immune response. "
Is it even possible to assess the strength of an immune system?
"When students were exposed to the flu virus, it was shown that those who did not sleep or were under higher stress were more susceptible to infection.
Besides, there are laboratory parameters that check the immune system or its components.
When there is a decrease in the immune system, you see it immediately.
People get a lot of viral or infectious diseases.
It's not like anyone walks around with a weak immune system and doesn't know it.
These are people who come to inquiries because of recurrent events of infectious diseases, and what affects the system are banal things: stress, nutrition, sleep.
By the way, we also don't want too strong an immune system, because it can cause autoimmune diseases. "
MRNA vaccines will soon appear in other contexts, thanks to the great knowledge that has accumulated about them in recent times.
"There is no doubt that other vaccines of this type will be opened.
This technology is being tested for many uses beyond vaccines - for treatments for oncological diseases, for example.
Their effectiveness is that the substance remains very little time in the body - enters, does its action, and then decomposes.
This technology is not new, but it has received a serious boost due to the very great need for a fast vaccine.
Now, for example, we know that the three-week interval between doses is too small, and some of the vaccine experts claim that after a third dose we may not need another vaccine in the near term, so it is not clear whether we are going to be vaccinated every six months or the third dose will give a larger interval. "
Thousands injured in serious privacy failure on Route 6
Route 6 customers?
Your personal information, including your full name, addresses, payment amounts, and full travel information may have been compromised.
According to the Privacy Protection Authority, Derech Eretz violated the Privacy Protection Law and its regulations.
After a report by Derech Eretz, the operator of Highway 6 in Israel, about a security incident that took place at the company, the Privacy Protection Authority began an enforcement process.
As part of the incident, security vulnerabilities were discovered on its payment site, which allowed the exposure of a lot of information from the invoices of the member's clients, which were exposed to all eyes.
Among other things, the customers "payment invoices were exposed over a period of time and these invoices included personal information, including first and last name, payment amounts, location of the vehicle, dates of travel and at what times.
In addition, since Derech Eretz did not record as required by law the access to its systems, it is not possible to know exactly for what period unauthorized parties could access the company's systems.
In the infringement letter, which was forwarded to the company by the Privacy Protection Authority, the authority emphasized that most of the large companies and organizations in the economy are required to adopt a dynamic information security policy, and that as threats and risks develop, the organization must carefully examine the updated risks and act in accordance with the update of customary security measures under the circumstances, in accordance with the nature and nature of the database.
As a result, companies and organizations are obligated to update their systems and conduct risk surveys and intrusion tests in order to examine and prepare for the changing risks.
In addition, companies and organizations are required to use an automatic documentation mechanism and to conduct trainings for employees, in accordance with the provisions of the Privacy Protection (Information Security) Regulations.
In accordance with the findings of the Supervision Department, the Authority determined that the company violated the provisions of the Privacy Protection Law and its regulations, and demanded that the company perform a number of corrective actions.
From Derech Eretz, Highway 6 operator said: "The issue was dealt with in accordance with the most stringent requirements"
